      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nThroughout human history, it has been common to view people as different—sometimes to the extreme of considering some groups inferior. This fact leads us to reflect:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On differences</b><br /><br />Is there any logic in considering others inferior?<br /><br />Did colonizers view Indigenous peoples as inferior?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_eurasia",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Differentiation in Eurasian History</h3>This study focuses on the peoples who dominated or inhabited the Iberian Peninsula prior to their arrival in the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>). Although the Vikings arrived earlier (<htcite0>), they did not establish colonies nor settle the region, possibly being repelled by native peoples (<htcite1>).</p><p>The Greeks and Romans classified peoples outside their empire as “barbarians,” a generic term that grouped together all neighbors of the Roman Empire (<htcite2>). The term was not only exclusionary but also strongly pejorative, as Suzanne Devallet notes (<htcite3>). Although persistent, this was not the only form of exclusion that shaped Iberian thought.</p><p>In Arab sources, a similar mentality is found in the writings of Ibn Khaldūn (<htcite4>). He described the Black people of Lamlam as invaded and enslaved (<htcite5>) and further claimed that:</p><p> <ul class=\"citation\"><li>\"Besides them, to the south, there is no civilization in the proper sense. There are only humans who are closer to stupid animals than to rational beings. They live in thickets and caves and eat unprepared herbs and grains. They often eat each other. They cannot be considered human beings.\"</li></ul></p><p>Although acknowledging them as human, Ibn Khaldūn established an artificial divide: on one side, the “rational”; on the other, the “irrational.”</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9c2fe063-9428-4706-b116-ddb07176bdc3",
                     "text": "Sanders, Ralph",
                     "page": "7 - 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "08"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "88294169-d7c1-4c98-9e73-a324470cd808",
                     "text": "McGhee, Robert",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1984",
