      {
         "id": "SECTION_european",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>The Aspiration to be “European”</h3>In Brazil, the notion of superiority persisted. Some authors, such as Pedro de A. T. Paes Leme and Luiz G. Silva Leme, even argued that Indigenous peoples descended from Europeans (<htcite0>). However, recent DNA studies reveal otherwise, showing the Indigenous origins of several Paulista matriarchs (<htcite1>).</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: About genealogical trees</b><span id=\"myFirstReflection\"></span></div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a8382521-89c3-4f67-b92e-b5d9ebcb50ad",
                     "text": "Schneider, Alberto L.",
                     "page": "pp. 99-100",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2016",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "29"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 3,
                     "uuid": "2b3c190a-a903-4066-adae-cd565147011b",
                     "text": "de Sillos, Luiz Gustavo",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
