      {
         "id": "SECTION_breed",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Races</h3>The social concept of \"race\", lacks biological foundation, despite ongoing disagreements (<htcite0> ; <htcite1> ; <htcite2>). Its persistence is tied to structural racism, which limits the advancement of certain groups (<htcite3>).</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-dna\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-earth-americas\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-infinity\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><b>Biology, Geography and Mathematic in History</b><br /><br />When discussing the concept of races in other species and excluding it for humans, we are not denying our differences but rather recognizing the complexity of the issue. As demonstrated by Alan R. Templeton in his research, geographical separations have influenced genetic diversity among human populations. However, when compared to the races of chimpanzees — our closest relatives in terms of DNA — these variations are so small that the concept of human races becomes meaningless (<htcite4> ; <htcite5> ; <htcite6>).</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
