      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Conclusion</h3>Historically, the notion of superiority among human groups has been used to justify domination—whether to reinforce social hierarchies (<htcite0>) or to facilitate conquest and exploitation (<htcite1>). This discourse, which devalued Indigenous peoples to legitimize territorial appropriation, continues to manifest itself in the early 21st century, according to Gregorian Calendar (<htcite2>).</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: On superiority</b><br /><br />Do you find it difficult to acknowledge that we are all equal, even if we have different tastes and preferences?<br />Why do you feel the need to see yourself as superior to others?<br />What makes your perspective more valid than someone else’s?<br />Is there a fear—either present or about an uncertain future—that leads you to believe in your own superiority?</div></div></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
